        {
            "title": "ExxonMobil's Beaumont, Texas, Refinery Reports Unit Upset : TCEQ Filing -- OPIS",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>\n  By Frank Tang; Editing by Michael Kelly </p><p>\n\n  ExxonMobil's 637,400 b/d Beaumont refinery on the Texas Gulf Coast reported a process unit upset, the oil major told the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality in a Wednesday filing. </p><!-- Article --><p>\n\n  In the TCEQ regulatory filing, ExxonMobil identified the process unit as a fluid catalytic cracking unit. The unit upset occurred early Tuesday, resulting in flaring and the release of multiple air contaminants that lasted for about 24 hours, it said. </p><p>\n\n  Process streams were routed to the flares to minimize emissions, the filing showed. The company said it expects to meet all contractual commitments. </p><p>\n\n  The Beaumont facility, located about 85 miles northeast of downtown Houston, is one of the largest oil refineries in the U.S. The integrated petrochemical complex built on the banks of the Neches River produces transportation fuels, building-block chemicals and lubricant base stocks, according to the oil major's website. </p><p>\n\n  (c) 2025 Oil Price Information Service, LLC. All rights reserved. </p><br/><p>\n  (END) Dow Jones Newswires</p><p>\n\n  10-09-25 1128ET</p></div>",
